animal.description:
Hippie is about 60lbs, and short. 
She is a couch potato that loves tummy rubs more than life itself.  This girl is really good at using pillows and blankets too! She's very quiet and loves humans of all sizes and ages. Hippie likes chew toys, but really loves stuffies and is very careful to make sure she is gentle with them so they last longer.  She likes to go on walks around the neighborhood, but would skip them if it's raining too hard and would rather just snuggle.  She's house & crate trained and has learned sit, stay, lay down, shake, and how to stay while her paws are wiped.  Hippie is a great road tripper and loves to go exploring new places. Hippie is still learning recall and should not be off-leash until she gets the hang of it. She's very gentle with young children and would probably love to have a human sibling. She has no history with cats. She has no issues with fireworks or loud noises, and loves to be in the room if music is playing.  She does have some separation anxiety, but is a great candidate for an office dog.

animal.description:
??Please read entire biography ??

Paco is an 8yr male neuter chi/jack russell mix. Through no fault of his own he is up for adoption. He is up to date on vaccines, heartworm neg, on hw preventative and flea/tick treatment.
Paco is house trained .  He gets along very well with other dogs.  He enjoys running around the fenced yard and going on walks.  He likes sitting on your lap and getting belly rubs.  He's a happy little guy and loves to play with toys.  He is just the cutest when he poses "puppy butt in the air" and races around in circles tail wagging a mile a minute.
Now for the challenging part Paco is his own worst enemy when it comes to meeting new people.  He likes to .... "talk alot of smack" and is quite intimidating.  He growls, barks, snarls and gladly shows his teeth.  He continues fiercely carrying on when being picked up until he really gets to know you. Once that happens he'll sit and as you go to lift him he'll do the dog equivalent of a toddler with arms up to be lifted (not lifting by front legs of course). His crate is his safe zone and he will defend it when inside.  He guards his toys unless he wants you to play with him.  Then he brings the toy to you and let's you know play time is about to commence.  He loves burrowing under your covers and is a great snuggler.  The problem is he wants to cuddle up but doesn't want to be petted.  Again the whole growling, snarling routine.  We were told he is very uncomfortable with children so an adult only home is required.  He has what the vet believes is a flea allergy so needs to be on a flea treatment every month.
I've fostered him for approximately a month.  He has NEVER bitten me regardless of what I have done and his intimidation technique.  He doesn't like his toes touched or nails trimmed which is certainly not rare in dogs so I strongly recommend a groomer with a muzzle as the best idea.
We're not sure where his bad attitude comes from.  He could be one of the little dogs that owners let get away with everything, with no structure and this is how they turn out.  Leaning over him makes him flinch and shy away so half squatting to pick him up is the way to go about it.  He has gotten so much better in the time he's been been here but still with the threat displays if you're trying to do something he's not 100% sure of.  He's fostered with 9 other dogs so a small part of the growling/snarling may be because he's worried the others will gang up on him in a perceived weak position.  I say a small part because he acts badly away from the other dogs also.
Paco really is a cute little guy who I feel will continue to improve in his attitude as he gets more comfortable.  He needs a confident and patient person to give him a chance to reach his true potential.  He needs to learn he doesn't call all the shots slowly and with empathy.
animal.name: Paco

animal.description:
We are so glad we could get Yula the medical care she needed! Now it's time to find her the adopter she deserves! Yula is a young adult hound mix who is about 2 years old and weighs 28-30 pounds. Yula was running loose with an injured back leg. No one claimed her so she came to us to get the vet are she needed. Yula's backleg could not be saved and was amputated. Yula barely seemed to notice! She has recovered well and it hardly slows her down! 

Yula is house trained and has good indoor manners. Her very favorite thing is to lounge and cuddle with her foster mom. She is very affectionate and bonds deeply to her person. Yula has not been exposed to other dogs in her foster home but is likely to be fine with proper introductions. 

Augusta Dog Adoptions is an all- volunteer, foster- based rescue. We take applications online and are scheduling individual adoptions in the Waynesboro, VA area during the pandemic.  A $175.00 adoption fee ($300 for puppies under 6 months old) helps us take care of all the dogs we rescue. All dogs are spayed/neutered, tested for heartworm and tick borne diseases (if old enough), microchipped, and vaccinated for rabies (if old enough), distemper/parvo and bordetella. They are also treated for internal and external parasites. Many dogs also receive extensive medical care such as dental work and major surgeries. For more information and to apply to adopt, please visit www.augustadogadoptions.org

animal.description:
Look into these golden eyes and you'll be mesmerized. Forrest is so typical to his breed; he loves to be with his people and doggie friends. We've witnessed this first hand as he whines to be let out of his confinement just to engage and be in the room. Not a high energy guy, but with a "Beagle Nose for scents, Forrest walks so great on a leash, pausing to give the air a sniff and see what's up that tree.

So why is Forrest being confined? You'd never know it now, but when we got him out of the Mesquite Shelter it was because he'd been brought in as a stray after being hit by a car. Unable to walk or even stand; Forrest had a broken pelvis and was in a great deal of pain. Without the aid of a rescue, he'd be just another statistic at the shelter. We were glad to step up for this boy and get him the medical attention he needed and the time to heal. His confinement was to ensure he didn't do too much while his body was on the mend, and today he limps occasional on his right rear leg but is so joyful and happy to be feeling better, it's hard to even notice. Due to the nature of this injury, his neuter will be delayed until late March of 2020, but it will get done!

He'd love a back yard to browse around in and a playmate to go with it, but his activity level will need to be closely monitored until he's reached full recovery of that injury.

Introducing Tate! 

Tate is a 3yo Deaf Double Merle Dane. He is house and crate trained and gets along with all dogs. Tate is an alpha male Dane. 

Tate will require an experienced Deaf Dane owner that can effectively manage a strong Alpha wannabe! No children under 15 for Tate. We are currently working though some of Tate’s behaviors with our trainer. He will be fully vetted, vaccinated and microchipped. 

We will require Tate to be in basic obedience training within 15 days of adoption.  Basic obedience training is a great opportunity for Tate to bond with his new family, learn new commands and reinforce good manners.  

For more information about our adoption process and an application please visit www.whitekissesgreatdanerescue.com

Want to bring me home? It's easy! All you have to do is fill out an application on our website: acadianaanimalaid.org/adopt/dog-adoption/application 

Our adoption fee is $225 for puppies and $205 for adults . All AAA dogs are up to date on all vaccinations, spayed or neutered, on heartworm preventative, and microchipped. 

Dogs are individuals -- The shelter software system requires that we choose a predominant breed or breed mix for our dogs. Visual breed identification in dogs is unreliable so for most of our dogs we are only guessing at predominant breed or breed mix. We encourage you to select your new companion by considering each dog's individual personality and pet qualities instead of relying on a breed label that is only a guess.

Livi is an 8 month old female mix. She currently weighs around 35 lbs. We love those stand up ears! Livi previously lived in a home with kids and other dogs. She currently lives in a foster home with kids, another dog, and a cat. Livi is an energetic puppy still, but not a “bounce off the walls” type. She would benefit greatly from consistency and training to help her reach full good girl potential. To add this cute girl to your family, apply to adopt at ITVrescue.org.

All of our animals are examined by a veterinarian, given age-appropriate vaccinations, dewormed, microchipped, spayed or neutered, heartworm tested and treated if necessary.

Please realize that many of our animals are kept in foster homes. Please complete an adoption application at http://itvrescue.org/adoption-application/ in order to meet with one of our animals. There is no obligation in completing the application, but it helps us find an animal that is most appropriate for your family.  The ITV Rescue Center is open Tuesdays 12-5; Wednesdays 12-7; Thursdays 12-5; Fridays 12-5 and Saturdays 10-5.  The Rescue Center is located at 1417 N. Stockwell Road.  You are welcome to come to our rescue center during open hours to see all of our great adoptable animals. Thank you for your interest in our animals!

NOTE: Visual breed identification in dogs is unreliable, so for most of the dogs we are only guessing at predominant breed or breed mix. We get to know each dog as an individual and will do our best to describe each of our dogs based on personality, not by breed label.

animal.description:
Needs: Fenced yard, rural area, experienced owner. No other dogs.


Major H.   is an energetic young Staffie mix. He loves his people.  
He loves to give kisses and and grunts when he receives attention. He can snore up a storm.  Major H. learns commands quickly.

Major H. is really hoping for a home of his own soon.  Because his foster family has so many dogs and he does not do well with that, he has to hang out in a separate area of the house all the time. That's no way  to live for a fellow that loves people so much long term. 

Mr. Handsome  walks lovely in forests or quiet side streets, but becomes difficult to manage in busy streets with dogs and children on scooters in hot pursuit.

So what does Major H.need?  A dog savvy owner that isn't perturbed when he joyfully wants to bounce up to say hello.. (we keep working on staying down) and that has a safely fenced back yard away from busy life and other dogs.  Preferably this young man would love  to live a country life with a person that he can adore.   Hugo's adoption donation is sponsored by his current foster family.. for a home that feels they can give this boy a chance.

Hugo crates well. 

If interested in adopting please fill out our no obligation online application at www.puppypawsrescue.org 

Note: Our rescue requires that all adopter's current and prior animals are up-to-date on vaccinations (DHLPP & Rabies)  and preventatives (heartworm and flea and tick), unless there is a medical reason not allowing it. All animals in your household should be spayed or neutered unless medically indicated that they should not be or are currently still too young.

animal.description:
Meet cute Payton! She is about 2 months old (DOB 11/23/2020). The family that surrendered this litter said the parents were Jack Russell/Lab and Pointer/Lab.  She is quite playful; she loves wrestling with other dogs and chewing on her squeaker toys. She is also a sweetheart who likes to hangout and cuddle with her foster mom in her down time. Payton is a more curious and adventurous puppy. She is working on puppy pad and crate training but is not at 100% yet. She would love to have another doggy playmate and doesn’t seem to mind cats. Payton would do best in a home with older kids (10+) because she can get a little feisty when she is in play mode. She will be a great addition to a family who will give her the socialization and training all puppies need.
PACA is a foster based rescue with no shelter to view our dogs. We have temporarily stopped all our public adoption events due to COVID-19, however we are still placing dog into loving homes by private appointment with approved applications.

Completed applications will be given to the foster to coordinate meetings as everyone feels comfortable. This application helps us get to know you and your family a little better so we can find the perfect match! Application are found here:
http://www.nmpaca.org/images/pdf_files/PACA_Adoption_Application.pdf
Please email completed applications to pacadogs@aol.com

All our animals are spayed or neutered, vaccinated, microchipped and tested for tic born illness and heartworm prior to adoption. Our fee is $175.

animal.description: This big dude is Enzo! Enzo came to us with his brother Killean. P Our friends at PETA rescued them from a life of neglect. Enzo lived all his young life in an outdoor pen. When we received him he was covered in mud, baring wounds, no manners, under socialized and heartworm positive. All signs of living outside without proper love and care. Since arriving here with his brother, Enzo has started to learn about the finer things in life. Such as medical treatment, walking on a leash ,simply receiving a badly needed bath and human love and affection.Enzo is a big puppy that needs, commitment, patience, consistency and love. He would benefit from a canine friend who can tolerate his puppy antics and pave the way for him. The folks who rescued him have so graciously sponsored his $780.00 heartworm treatment. His new family will only need to keep the big beast calm during treatment. When not attended Enzo should be crated. He is not use to living in the comforts of a home. His new family will have to be ready to teach him how to be a loved member of a family. Enzo has never lived with children. this big guy can easily knock a small child over with force, not meaning to of course. We are requiring that any children in the home be 12 years and over. After HW treatment Enzo will need and active life style. He is a mix of three very high energy dogs ( Lab, GSD Aussie). Enzo would love a home with a huge fenced yard, After he is medically cleared he wants to celebrate being heartworm free with a giant case of zoomies in his new home.If you are interested in meeting this hunk please ask today.

animal.description: This sweet, energetic dog with the amazing smile is Zoey! Zoey came to us as a transfer from a rural shelter so we do not know anything about her past. However we can tell you that she was not cared for properly. Our sweet Zoey has heartworm disease. Luckily she is here with us and she will be treated. Her new family will need to pay for her treatment. It is a very small price to pay, when giving the gift of life. Heartworm disease can be deadly going untreated. Zoey has not been socialized around the little ones, so any children in the home should be at least 10 years of age or older. Zoey is very deserving of a family who will love and care for her through the rest of her life. Zoey dreams of blue skies, grassy hills, a comfy couch, being heartworm free, romps around the fields and humans that love her to no end. Will you make her dreams come true? Please ask to meet Zoey today.

animal.description:
Roscoe is a 7 mo. old dachshund/basset hound mix and a bundle of fun! 
His family had to surrender him due to these trying times. He is neutered and up to date on all of his shots. He is too young for a heart worm test at this time. Roscoe is micro chipped. 
We understand that his Mom was a dachshund and Daddy unknown.  We suspect some Basset hound due to his precious out turned kankles. He might have a touch of a Baby Yoda in his very expressive ears. 
He is 30lbs. Long and low. He is a fabulous family pet. Funny and smart. He hits the bells on the door to go out. He doesn’t love the kennel. Wanting to be a lap dog he follows his hoomans with great dedication! 
Roscoe is playful with dogs and children, cats unknown. He loves love and he loves to give it! He is a pure joy!

Please note: as with most rescue puppies, we have no way to guarantee this puppy’s breed or size potential. 

*Take Paws Rescue saves dogs from high-kill shelters in Southeast Louisiana, owner surrenders, and discarded dogs with uncertain futures. All of our puppies live in foster homes where they are socialized, and well cared for. An application will be required to make sure it’s the perfect match!

 If you are interested in meeting and/or adopting, the first step is to please visit our website to complete an application and read all of our FAQs: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/adopt 

**An inquiry/question on Petfinder is NOT an application. All known details about our animals are posted on their profile and updated daily. Other info would be discussed in detail with the foster during the application review process. Due to the number of inquires received (hundreds daily) we ask you submit an application on our website (a single application can be used for any dog with Take Paws Rescue).

The adoption fee for adult dogs covers age appropriate vaccinations, microchip, spay/neuter if not yet performed, heartworm test & appropriate heartworm treatment by the rescue's vet. All dogs in our care are also kept up-to-date on HW/Flea Prevention. Please see our website for more information. 

2021 Adoption Fee Scale for non-benefactor animals:
Puppies under 12 months - $300
Dogs over 12 months - $200

For additional information, including the adoption process and our adoption fee scale for all our adoptable pets, see our FAQs page: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/faq

*Any breed labels used by Take Paws Rescue, its employees/volunteers, or on vet records provided cannot be guaranteed.  Breed labels are given based on information obtained during intake and/or best guesses based on appearance and/or temperament of the dogs and Take Paws Rescue gives no assurance to the accuracy of these labels. Labels are necessary for postings to many animal networking sites, such as Pet Finder, and are no way a guarantee. Additionally, exact age and potential size cannot be guaranteed.

animal.description:
Meet George - 

George is a beautiful Doberman that turned 3 in October 2020. He gets complimented on his markings frequently when we go walking. George was rescued from a breeder/hoarder situation and was placed with his foster family at the beginning of December. He seems to have some minor loss of vision but he can see well enough to enjoy life. He bonded quickly with his foster mom, and has improved tremendously with meeting others in the past couple months. He is incredibly loving and sweet.  George knew from the beginning not to go potty in the house and is crate trained. His crate is his safe spot and initially he would go there when he needed down time. As he has gotten comfortable, he spends less time in the crate and seems happy to lay on his bed near us. He sleeps in his crate at bedtime and doesn’t make a peep all night. His personality has been evolving as he becomes more confident. He has become very playful and more vocal, making a whining noise like he is talking to us. He has met a couple other dogs and we believe that he would do well in a house with another dog that could play with him, teach him, and give him confidence. George is smart, fast learner and eager to please. George would love a yard to play in.  He loves his walks and spends a lot of time sniffing everything. Due to George’s past and compromised vision, he may startle easily with noises or fast movements.  He is continually getting more accustomed to living the pet life, and he is very appreciative of the comforts of his foster home.  A home with children over 16 that is willing to give George some time to adjust is recommended. Cats are an unknown.
PACA is a foster based rescue with no shelter to view our dogs. We have temporarily stopped all our public adoption events due to COVID-19, however we are still placing dog into loving homes by private appointment with approved applications.

Completed applications will be given to the foster to coordinate meetings as everyone feels comfortable. This application helps us get to know you and your family a little better so we can find the perfect match! Application are found here:
http://www.nmpaca.org/images/pdf_files/PACA_Adoption_Application.pdf
Please email completed applications to pacadogs@aol.com

All our animals are spayed or neutered, vaccinated, microchipped and tested for tic born illness and heartworm prior to adoption. Our fee is $175.

animal.description:
If you are interested in adopting this dog, please download and complete the Adoption Questionnaire and email Michelle at mhunt@k-9lifesavers.org
You can find PDF, Word and ONLINE versions of the adoption questionnaire by visiting our website at: http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/howtoadopt/
Dog's Name: Frank
Estimated Breed: Feist Mix
Approximate Age: 8 years
Approximate Weight: 25-30 lbs
Currently Living at: boarding
Adoption Fee: $200
DOG'S DESCRIPTION
Frank is an adorable mature, easy going gentleman of simple needs and few demands. A gentle natured soul, he is most happy with human companionship. He will enjoy joining you on walks that stick to the path (with the occasional sniffing of the "roses") and at the end of the day he will sit at your feet with his little head perched on the edge of the couch. He isn't too fond of other dogs and would rather have all of the love and attention to himself. Who is ready for some love in their life?
Your new pet will require a refresher in house-training. K-9 Lifesavers cannot guarantee that our dogs won't have accidents in their new home, even if they are fully house broken in their current foster home as they have to adjust to new environment, routine, and schedule. K-9 Lifesavers strongly recommends all new adopters enroll their new pet into obedience training. This provides for an easier transition into a new home, ensures the dog remains well socialized, and helps form a bond between the dog and the new family.
Adoption fees cover basic vetting, rabies, distemper/parvo vaccinations, treatment for worms, heartworm testing, monthly heartworm prevention (while in our care), monthly flea/tick prevention, and our transport costs. As part of the adoption agreement, adopters agree to get the pup spayed/neutered by 6 months of age. K-9 Lifesavers do not cover the cost of spay/neuter for puppies 6 months and younger.
Foster Program: Foster homes provide for the temporary care of a rescue until the dog is placed into a loving, forever home. For more information on becoming a foster parent, and our Foster Program, visit http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/foster/ or email our Foster Coordinator at foster@k-9lifesavers.org
Help Save Lives! Make a tax-deductible donation today by clicking on the Donate Button below! Donations help us offset boarding costs and additional medical treatment for those dogs who need it. K-9 Lifesavers receives NO federal funding and survive with your generous support!
For more information on K-9 Lifesavers, or to view a complete listing of all our Adoptable Dogs, visit our website at www.k-9lifesavers.org.
Check out our social media! Search for us on Facebook, Twitter, Pinterest and Instagram!!
Thank you for considering a rescue dog!

SPONSOR ME!
We are all volunteer, non-profit organization. We spend on average $600 per dog while our adoption fees range from $300-$375. We are only able to continue our work thanks to generous donations from public. Please consider supporting our rescue's mission with your donation.
Visit: http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/donate/

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Shane is an adorable brindle colored mixed breed dog. He loves to be around people and is
good natured with his household. He loves playing fetch, tug of war, car rides and going on
long walks. He likes cuddling on the couch while watching TV or sitting on your lap while you read. He loves a seat by the window so he can watch people in the neighborhood. Shane is highly intelligent and easily learns new things. While with us he quickly learned to sit, shake, lay down and stay. His favorite chore is bringing in the Sunday newspaper. He also figured out that we only let him on the couch in the family room, a rule he easily follows. When he is uncomfortable he communicates it clearly. He has seen cats and taken an interest in them but has not met one up close. He does not mind being in his crate, but sometimes needs a bribe to go in it. Shane would fit in best as the only dog in the home and one that has older children. Available end of January for adoption once he finishes his heart worm treatment.

We were asked to help with dogs that were affected by Hurricane Laura. In Sulphur Louisiana, a very remote area between Lake Charles and the Texas border, there are lots of small rescues.

animal.description: Cyrus is a beautiful and fluffy Akita mix that is fixed and estimated to be around 3 years old. He has Lyme's Disease but that doesn't slow him down. He should be in a household that doesn't have younger children under 13. This way the children know the boundaries especially with having this particular breed. He is friendly, affectionate, independent, and loves to play. He won't turn down treats and he knows sit, paw, stay, and down. He can be a little stubborn sometimes. He doesn't jump on people and walks well on the leash. Cyrus just finished obedience training so come and let him show you his tricks. He is good with cats and dogs, he was also in a house with a rat. You should not disturb him while he is sleeping, just like other dogs, because that will startle him and the outcome may not be a good one. He will nudge you when he needs to go outside. animal.description:
Hi friends!! My name is Veneta and I am 7 months old! 

I have LOTS of energy and love to play with other dogs but I don’t quite understand boundaries yet so I need a dog brother or sister who is very patient. I can intimidate small dogs because I want to play so bad and don’t realize it can be intimidating! I haven’t been around kids before, but I’m sure I’d love to play with them! But they need to be big enough that I won’t knock them down while playing because I am still learning coordination and control over my body. I have a lot of energy so I’d do best with a backyard to run around in and sticks to chew up! I love adventuring, so I make a great running and hiking buddy. 

When I am not playing outside or playing tug of war with my foster mom, I LOVE to snuggle. I’ll curl up next to you while you watch t.v. or read a book. I am potty trained! When I go to new places, it takes me a little bit to remember my training but once I do, I almost never have accidents! I stay in my crate while my foster mom isn’t home and I sleep in my crate at night... but occasionally I look extra cute and my foster mom lets me sleep with her:) 

I love everybody and have yet to meet a human who I’m not excited to meet! I hope one of you will adopt me and show me lots of attention, love, and patience... and maybe even give me a few treats!

I am up to date on shots, microchip and spayed for the adoption fee of $150. If interested in adopting me please email adoptions.spspca@gmail.com

animal.description:
Hi, I'm Chief! I'm a silly six year old boy rescued from a Virginia Shelter. When I arrived at the Rescue in November, I was a terrible mess. My eyes were swollen with the lids rolled in about three time, and my ears were full of infection and swollen shut. We started with lots of meds to reduce swelling and help with the infections. Then on 12/3, I had entropion surgery to fix my eyes and was neutered at the same time. I also had a lump on my head and a skin tag on my eyelid removed. I am recovering well at my Foster home and will be ready for adoption soon.

I'm a love bug and like to be close to my people. I've made some new Pei friends here at my foster home - Muffy and Finn!

animal.description:
Roscoe George now known as Jasper is a stunning 5 year old Great Pyrenees weighing a little over 100 lbs.  He loves to be groomed, brushed and given pampering.  He does very good when clipping his toenails for his routine pedicure.  He loves kisses and hugs and will let you pet and rub on him all day long!   

This precious guy has lived a very rough life where he was rescued in Louisiana. His life prior to coming to CAFA rescue involved him being chained to a tree since he was a puppy with no shelter during all weather conditions (rain, cold, sleet, thunderstorms).  This poor guy had to endure it all alone and nothing to protect him from the elements. Roscoe was extremely emaciated, severe ear infection and strong heart worm positive when we took him.  He trust people unless you are wearing a hat which we believe triggers something from his past.  He seems to become uneasy at night and a bit unsure at times.  Fast movements tend to scare him and sometimes he seems to be uneasy especially at night.  He does not like loud noises such as piano playing, crowd noises from football games, sirens, loud construction noises or fast movements which are all things related to his past we believe.  

What HE DOES LOVE is LONG naps, a nice meal, hugs and kisses, grooming, and a quiet household,  He is good with other dogs but will herd them as that is his breed.  Since he loves all the attention and TLC, we think he would be best in a home with no other dogs and his families only four legged canine love!  He is good with children and will allow them to brush and pet him but we feel he would be best in a home without children since he does not like fast movements and loud noises and busy households.  He  is also food aggressive so he needs to be fed separately because he was starved to death, tied to this tree forcing him to starve to death, is why he has these behaviors.  

Roscoe likely lived with chronic ear infections, as his ear canals appear to have old scarring from repeat infections. In addition, he chewed on the chain that bound him to his tree causing his teeth to be very worn down and his canine teeth had some exposed pulp. Since he has been in New England, he has had fourteen teeth removed and is in much better and has a great new smile as you can see in his video.

He would love a quiet family with a big fenced yard to roam around. He wants cuddles, and would love a comfy doggie bed inside to cuddle and take those long naps he loves so much.  He will sit on command and is very proud of himself when he pleases you.

Roscoe is a very special boy that will need a special home who understands his needs and quirks.  

Adoption fees details: 
Puppies - Adults $ 550, Seniors $375. These adoption rates include transport from Alexandria, Louisiana to designated New England adopter pick up locations and NE foster homes using either Rescue Road Trips, Pets LLC or CAFA Transport. If you do a search you will see that this is a very reasonable adoption fee and comparable to other rescues. Adoption fee breakdown:Adoption Fee:   $  365.00Transportation Fee:  $ 185.00MA and NH only--Quarantine fee if applicable:  $125.00

Medical details:
All our dogs are altered (spayed or neutered), DHLPP, rabies, Bordetella, Heartworm tested with negative test results, microchipped, treated for parasites and on monthly heartworm and flea and tick prevention. A health certificate is issued by a licensed Louisiana veterinarian.

Adoption details:  
In some instances, a meet and greet is not possible before adoption unless we have a foster home in New England available. Available for a Meeting confirms the dog is in a NE Foster home and available for a meeting in the city state provided.  Most times our dogs get adopted before a foster home becomes available - and if so, they go straight to adopters home. Foster parents talk to adopters and feel confident that this will be a match before our dogs are transported up. Also if by some chance it is not a match we have a safety net in place as we ask that adopters to let us know that it is not a match and we direct you to take the dog to a foster home or boarding kennel once that is arranged. If necessary, we will ask you to foster the dog until a foster home can be arranged. 
Transport details:Rescue Road Trips (rescueroadtrips.com), Pets LLC (petsllc.net) or CAFA Transport will deliver our precious pups on commercial rescue animal transport to designated locations.  The fee is 185.00 which IS INCLUDED in your adoption fee already.**Rescue Road Trips, was featured on The Today Show - view it at http://www.today.com/video/today/55034556#55034556

MA and NH RESIDENTS:
If you are a Massachusetts or New Hampshire residence, an additional fee of $125.00 will apply due to State quarantine fee requirements. If the dog is in a foster home in MA or NH, this fee will be added in the adoption fee regardless of where the adopters home is located making the total adoption fee $675.00 for puppies and adults $500.00 for Seniors, otherwise the full adoption fee for all other states is $550.00 for puppies and adults and $375.00 for seniors. This includes a 48 quarantine, recheck by a MA licensed veterinarian, and issued a MA health certificate.

Visit all our available dogs at www.cenlaallianceforanimals.comWe update and add dogs frequently.

We hope to help make a difference in a rescue dogs life into loving responsible homes.

animal.description:
Hi, my name is Teague. I'm a bit of a shy girl at first, but once I learn to trust you, I'll follow you to the ends of the Earth. A nice lady is currently fostering me and showing me the kindness of humans, so I'd like to find my very own family to give me that same kindness and love. I get along well with my feline roommates, as you can see. On walks I get excited when I see other dogs, but if you ask me to pay attention to you, I'll rein it in and be a good girl. Ideally, I'd love to find a home with people who are familiar with fearful dogs like me, understand I will need some time before I feel comfortable enough to come out of my shell and show my sweet and silly side. I really like receiving positive reinforcement as feedback; I learn and trust people more quickly that way!  I really love snuggling with my people curled up next to them on the sofa or bed. I'm house trained and pretty chill indoors. 

If you're interested in Teague, please email us at: adopt@gigis.org. She is current on vaccinations, microchipped and spayed. She's rated PG-15, good with cats, and will probably be fine with other dogs through proper introductions. She is currently in foster care and doing very well.

Due to the high number of emails we receive, we will not be responding to any inquiries. If interested, please apply on our website, www.luckytalesrescue.org. As long as the pet is viewable, we are accepting applications. No matter the outcome, we will email all applicants once the dog has been adopted. Thank you for your understanding.

**
Hello all, my name is Milo and I’m a 1.5 year old 50 lb. Shar Pei/Lab mix. When I was taken in by my foster mom, I was really scared. I would pee if anyone raised their voice for any reason and would cry in my cage at night. It was tough on me! But with a lot of love and patience, my foster mom has brought me out of that shell and I am now confident and happy.

I live with 2 human siblings and one 4-legged brother and I love them all! I love to investigate the back yard when I’m allowed, and I love my chew toys and stuffed animals, but for the most part I like to just chill with my foster family.

My foster mom calls me Mellow Milo because it fits me perfectly, just like my sweet droopy face! I mean you can’t go wrong with me, so how bout it?! Not to mention, I'm crate trained and house trained, too. 

I am up to date on vaccinations, microchipped, heartworm negative, and neutered. 
My adoption fee is $200?

animal.description:
If you are interested in adopting this dog, please download and complete an Adoption Questionnaire from our website and email Michelle at mhunt@k-9lifesavers.org
You can learn about the adoption process and find a Word, PDF and ONLINE version of the questionnaire by visiting: http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/howtoadopt/.
Dog's Name: Denali
Estimated Breed : American Bulldog Mix
Approximate Age: 1 year
Approximate Weight: approx. 35 lbs
Currently Living at: Boarding
Adoption Fee: $375
DOG'S DESCRIPTION
Denali just loves people and laps up all the cuddles and affection he can get! He is very sweet but shy about new things, so will need a patient home to warm up to. He is friendly but will do best with submissive males and/or females. He would do best with an adult only home or children over 16 as he sudden movements can be a little too much for him. Unfortunately, he is heartworm positive. But don't let that scare you away from this loving boy! We will provide his treatment and he will be a great addition to one lucky loving family!
Your new pet will require a refresher in house-training. K-9 Lifesavers strongly recommends all new adopters enroll their new pet into obedience training. This provides for an easier transition into a new home, ensures the dog remains well socialized, and helps form a bond between the dog and the new family.
Adoption fees cover basic vetting, spay/neuter surgery (for dogs over 6 months old), rabies, distemper/parvo vaccinations, treatment for worms, heartworm testing, monthly heartworm prevention and monthly flea/tick prevention (while the animal is in our care), and transport costs from high-kill shelter. Please note that on average, K-9 Lifesavers spend significantly more on each dog than their adoption fee. Adoption fee for HW positive dog also covers heartworm treatment at our partner vets.
Foster Program: Foster homes provide for the temporary care of a rescue until the dog is placed into a loving, forever home. For more information on becoming a foster parent, and our Foster Program, visit http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/foster/ or email our Foster Coordinator at foster@k-9lifesavers.org
Sponsor Me! Make a tax-deductible donation today by visiting us at http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/donate/ . Donations help us offset boarding costs and additional medical treatment for those dogs who need it. K-9 Lifesavers receives NO federal funding and survive with your generous support!
For more information on K-9 Lifesavers, or to view a complete listing of all our Adoptable Dogs, visit our website at www.k-9lifesavers.org.
Please "like" our Facebook Page for the most current events and new dogs.
Thank you for considering a rescue dog!

animal.description:
Hey, I'm Sammi! I’m an approximately 2-year-old American Eskimo mix who will not give you the cold shoulder. In fact, I love nothing better than nonstop pets on my super-soft, dazzling white coat. At 19 pounds, I'm just the right weight to keep your lap toasty warm on frosty nights. Fair warning though, I do take a beat or two to warm up to people…hey, you can't go around doling out eskimo kisses willy-nilly!

I am housebroken as long as I am kept on a schedule. I don't do well in a crate but do okay if relegated to a room, like a kitchen with a baby gate — that way I can stretch my legs a bit. I’m a good friend: I get along well with my foster's dogs, respecting the older Chihuahua and playing chase and tug with the younger fluffy one.  

I am not picky at all when it comes to food. Heck, after living on the streets of Chicago, getting regular meals of kibble is wonderful. While I do okay on walks, I'm still leery of the harness and sort of jump around whenever my foster tries to put it on, but I am getting a bit better. I do pretty well in a car, either in a crate or clipped in with a seatbelt harness, to keep me safe.

Even though the vet thinks I'm around 2, I have a lot of puppy in me and get mouthy at times. That is something I will need my new people to continue to work on and a reason why I probably wouldn't be the best fit for a home with really young kids.

Well, that's about it from me. If your igloo needs warming, then fill out an application now!

Interested in adopting this dog? Visit our website (http://www.SecondCityCanineRescue.org) to fill out an application and to find out where this dog may be shown this weekend.

We love our dogs. We want happy lives for all of them and are looking for the home that provides the best fit for each dog’s individual needs. Please understand that there may be multiple families interested in this dog. 

Also, please know that the breed mix listed is simply a guess. In most cases, we don’t know their background. We encourage you to base your decision on individual personality and pet qualities instead of relying on our guess.

Please understand, we only adopt our animals out near the Chicagoland area. Questions? Email us at adoptions@sccrescue.org. Hope to see you become part of the SCCR family!

animal.description: Jake is another sweet senior in need of a swift exit from the shelter! Jake has a bit of a receding hairline suspected to be from hypothyroidism, but hey- lots of old men are losing their hair, right? The PACC clinic is working on it though! Jake was primarily an outdoor pet in his prior home, so at his age, is really in need of an indoor retirement situation. Heres what we know from Jakes former owner: - He's good with cats (hes a unicorn!) - He gets along great with kids (would do best with older kids who know how to appropriately interact with pets) - He loves to play in the pool and will jump right in - He knows sit and stay - He loves to be near his people and will sit at their feet while watching tv - He was housebroken for the most part when allowed indoors (give him some time to adjust in a new environment please!) When meeting other dogs in PACC playgroup, Jake was appropriate and tolerant with greetings, but mostly kept to himself. Jake needs to meet any resident pets before heading home to make sure they have all the important things in common- politics, religion, snack preferences the basics. Ask to meet Jake today!

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Hello, my name is Lucky! I am a young Feist mix looking for my forever family that will spoil me with praise, belly rubs and keep me active.

I am very smart and eager to learn. I love to make my foster mom proud whenever I get a chance. My house training is making great progress and I already know that my kennel is a safe spot. I like it better when it's covered with a blanket - it instantly calms me.

One of my favorite things to do is dig and run through the snow in the backyard with my dog pal Frankie. It's typical for my breed to try to nip at heels when I'm around other dogs or cats, but I am not aggressive and I respond well to redirection. Speaking of cats, I am curious about the ones that currently live with me, so together with the help of my foster family and the resident dog I have learned to understand their language better. We seem to get along best when I respect their space, so I gave up chasing them for the most part. In exchange we share the bed for naps while my foster mom works on her computer and I let them take a sip from my water bowl. If my forever family already has another dog I am hoping my new buddy would be similar in size so we can wrestle and play tug of war. It's fun for me to spend time with teenagers and older kids, but I haven't had experience being around any little ones so far.

Being patient around food was hard for me at first, but now that I know there is always plenty for everyone I won't try stealing it when someone tells me that they aren't sharing. It's still tempting for me, so my foster mom keeps it out of my reach in between feeding times and instead keeps toys and bones around for me me to chew on.

I don't mind walking on a leash at all, though I'd rather spend my outside time in the yard with my teenage foster brothers throwing balls or sticks for me to fetch, which is a new game I learned. Since I am an alert and curious dog I pay attention to most things that make noise or move. If I get a chance to sit by a window you'll catch me being entertained by watching squirrels and cars driving by and you'll likely only hear a short bark from me to alert you when I see something that's unfamiliar. I am getting really good at reading my foster mom's clues as to whether she expects me to chill or if it's okay when I try to investigate what's going on. She appreciates how loyal I am and how quickly I catch on to new rules.

Adoption fee includes: Full veterinary exam, alter, prepaid microchip, dewormed, Rabies vaccine, DAPP vaccine, Bordetella vaccine, 4DX

, flea/tick and heartworm preventative while in rescue. Adoption fee: $395.00

animal.description:
Amanda is an 18 month old Shepherd mix looking for her forever home.  She is a very sweet girl who loves to play with other dogs, but we do not know if she is happy with cats.  She is a lover of all humans.  If you would like to learn more about Amanda, please complete an application and then reach out to Roxy@bigfluffydogs.com

If you are interested in adopting this dog, please apply online, at https://bigfluffydogs.com/adopt/adoption-application/. 

Our main website, www.bigfluffydogs.com has more information about us and the rescue process. 

NOTE TO EMAILERS FROM PETFINDER: WE DO NOT RESPOND TO EMAIL INQUIRIES WITHOUT AN APPLICATION. WE REGRET WE CANNOT RESPOND TO EVERY EMAIL, BUT UNLESS YOU FILL OUT AN APPLICATION, WE DO NOT KNOW YOU EXIST. 

All known information about an individual dog is provided in its listing. We do our best to provide accurate information, but adopters should understand that each home is different and the dog may behave differently in a new home. Dogs are creatures of their environment and you help make the dog what it will be. Homes considering adopting a puppy must be prepared for 1.) Flexible schedules for potty training. Puppies can only hold it for one hour per month of age (i.e. a 4-month-old puppy can only go 4 hours without a potty break). 2.) Crate training until the puppy is at least one year old to prevent chewing on inappropriate things when you can't supervise. 3.) Socialization.  The more positive and varying experiences as a puppy the better, both in and out of your home. 4.) Puppy behavior and life stages are equivalent to a human toddler. It takes at least a full year to have a calmer, well-adjusted dog. Patience is required and when your dog's behavior is a positive experience for you and those around you, your patience will be rewarded ten-fold, for years to come.  Please do not consider adopting a puppy if you have not thoroughly thought through the pros and cons of having one. So many people end up returning them after 3-5 months because they didn't realize the amount of work involved in raising a puppy.  Patience, appropriate toys, socialization, and obedience training are all musts. All are time-consuming and can be expensive. All dogs require supervision with children and obedience training. Adopters that want to have good dogs must be prepared to put the time and effort into training a dog. Any dog requires work and effort, but a well trained, well-socialized dog is more than worth the effort to get them there.

If you are interested in adopting this dog, please download and complete an Adoption Questionnaire from our website and email US at

michelel@k-9lifesavers.org

You can learn about the adoption process and find a Word, PDF and ONLINE version of the questionnaire by visiting: http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/howtoadopt/.

Dog's Name: Bentley

Estimated Breed : Lab Mix

Approximate Age: 3 years

Approximate Weight: approx. 50 lbs

Currently Living at: Boarding

Adoption Fee: $300

DOG'S DESCRIPTION

This gorgeous little outlaw will steal your heart. He loves everybody and will take all the pets he can get! Bentley would love to find a loving family and forever home that will give him a chance to show his loyalty.

Your new pet will require a refresher in house-training. K-9 Lifesavers strongly recommends all new adopters enroll their new pet into obedience training. This provides for an easier transition into a new home, ensures the dog remains well socialized, and helps form a bond between the dog and the new family.

Adoption fees cover basic vetting, spay/neuter surgery (for dogs over 6 months old), rabies, distemper/parvo vaccinations, treatment for worms, heartworm testing, monthly heartworm prevention and monthly flea/tick prevention (while the animal is in our care), and transport costs from high-kill shelter. Please note that on average, K-9 Lifesavers spend significantly more on each dog than their adoption fee. Adoption fee for HW positive dog also covers heartworm treatment at our partner vets.

Foster Program: Foster homes provide for the temporary care of a rescue until the dog is placed into a loving, forever home. For more information on becoming a foster parent, and our Foster Program, visit http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/foster/ or email our Foster Coordinator at foster@k-9lifesavers.org

Sponsor Me! Make a tax-deductible donation today by visiting us at http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/donate/ . Donations help us offset boarding costs and additional medical treatment for those dogs who need it. K-9 Lifesavers receives NO federal funding and survive with your generous support!

For more information on K-9 Lifesavers, or to view a complete listing of all our Adoptable Dogs, visit our website at www.k-9lifesavers.org.

Please "like" our
Facebook Page
for the most current events and new dogs.

Thank you for considering a rescue dog!

animal.description:
Jackson is a bouncy, happy guy who has been starved for attention and neglected for too long. While we don't know the specifics of his history, we can surmise that he had been an outside dog until he came to us, likely confined to a kennel with a dog house. He came to us by way of the Perry County Dog Shelter as an unclaimed stray and tested positive for heartworm disease. He has been in our vet's care for several months now as he underwent treatment for his heartworm disease as well as learning to live like an inside dog and enjoying every day attention and individualized walks. He is an energetic guy and looks forward to playing in the snow this winter with his new family and then curling up on a new dog bed to dream of all the good things to come. Jacks is very sweet and loving; However, he's not suited for living with cats and will do best if not exposed to other dogs--he lived with other dogs in his foster home but that was after a very slow controlled introduction. We are estimating him to be a middle-aged (maybe 5-6ish) dog, likely Lab and another sporting breed mix. He is approximately 70lbs. Vet reference required; No invisible fence and would do best with a 6ft privacy fence.

This is a lovely note from a family who kept Jackson for a week, unfortunately he was not a good fit for them, but they were hoping this would help him find the right home:

Jackson is very affectionate and loves to sit, sleep,
and walk close to you. He made us think of the
traits of a golden retriever.
We noticed that he is anxious when separated.
He did not like to be crated but he accepted his
"fate" and joyfully embraced your return. That
might all change once he settles into your home
and knows this is his safe place.
He loves baby carrots and ice cubes for snacks.
He loves to trash pick tissues from open trash cans
and is a counter surfer. House training was easy,
just had to be shown where to go. He paces when
he needs to go outside. He is eager to please so
with training those issues will be eliminated.
We believe he will be best placed in a home with a
fence and no cats. Wait to introduce other dogs.
He LOVES to chase squirrels which is great in the
yard, not so good when walking him. Trainable fix.
Jackson will warm your heart and be a great addition
to any family. He loves children. Avoid balls and
stuffed toys that squeak. He loves to carry them
around but tears up for the squeaker.
Love him and he will return that love 110%.
 Primary Color: Brown Weight: 70lbs Age: 5yrs 0mths 1wks Animal has been Neutered

Pierre is a precious phantom-colored toy poodle about 3 years old and 5 pounds. His owner couldn’t keep him and asked us to accept him into our program. 

IF YOU'RE INTERESTED IN ADOPTING THIS DOG:
Please go to our Website: Poodlerescueofhouston.org and see the section: "Steps 2 Adoption". There will be a drop down menu where you must read and meet all of the prerequisites. Next, read the "Steps To Adoption", fill out the "Interest Form" and submit it online. THIS IS THE ONLY WAY TO APPLY. Unfortunately, we are unable to respond to inquires made in any other way.

Poodle Rescue will contact you if we feel this dog, or a similar dog in our program, matches the specifications on your Questionnaire/Interest Form. Please keep in mind Poodles and Poodle Mixes are in high demand therefore the demand for them far outweigh the supply. If you do not hear from us please re-submit your Interest form quarterly as they are not recurring. Unfortunately, we cannot answer email or telephone inquiries about our available dogs.  Please be sure you have a current phone number listed on the questionnaire/Interest Form and the best time we can reach you. Adoption Fees vary.

All dogs are spayed/neutered, current on shots, parasite / heart worm disease tested (and treated if positive).  All dogs are microchipped, groomed and use a dog door at our facility.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Name: Ren
Age: DOB 6/15/2011
Gender: Male
Breed: Shiba Inu
Weight: 18 lbs
Dog friendly: Yes
Cat friendly: Unknown
Kid friendly: 16+ only
House Trained: Yes
Crate Trained: In progress
Energy level: Moderate
History: From a reservation in South Dakota
Adoption Fee: $300

From the Foster:
Ren is a senior dude looking for a calm home to spend the remainder of his days. He is a stereotypical shiba: independent, aloof and alert to his surroundings. His ideal adopter will understand the temperament and personality of shibas. He has a very cat-like personality. He would rather sit off to the side and keep an eye on things instead of being in the action and would prefer to get attention only when he wants it. His favorite activity has been to sit at the sliding glass door and keep an eye on the backyard. He ignores my resident dogs and hasn't initiated or returned offers to play. He also has not shown interested in toys.

Ren is a very jumpy and easy to spook dog. Noises and movements scare him (even things on the TV), so he would do best in a quiet home with no children. He would not appreciate a loud and busy home. Ren also does not like being on a leash and will not walk on one, so he needs a secured fenced in yard. He currently does not have any recall and definitely has "selective" hearing when it comes to being called. Ren is not a food motivated dog and training him to like the leash and on better recall will require patience. Ren will most likely lose all of his teeth at his upcoming dental cleaning.

Must have fence, no kids under 16

If you are interested in adopting this dog, please download and complete an Adoption Questionnaire from our website and email jessalynL@k-9lifesavers.org
You can learn about the adoption process and find a Word, PDF and ONLINE version of the questionnaire by visiting: http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/howtoadopt/.
Dog's Name: Waffles
Estimated Breed : Terrier Mix
Approximate Age: 1 year
Approximate Weight: approx. 35 lbs
Currently Living at: Boarding
Adoption Fee: $300
DOG'S DESCRIPTION
This sweet little miss is a bundle of joy, super smart and loves to learn. Waffles is a super sweet and energetic dog who adores people. She has a lot of energy so will need regular exercise but will make a great dog. She will need leash work as she likes to pull. She would be so happy to find a loving family and forever home!
Your new pet will require a refresher in house-training. K-9 Lifesavers strongly recommends all new adopters enroll their new pet into obedience training. This provides for an easier transition into a new home, ensures the dog remains well socialized, and helps form a bond between the dog and the new family.
Adoption fees cover basic vetting, spay/neuter surgery (for dogs over 6 months old), rabies, distemper/parvo vaccinations, treatment for worms, heartworm testing, monthly heartworm prevention and monthly flea/tick prevention (while the animal is in our care), and transport costs from high-kill shelter. Please note that on average, K-9 Lifesavers spend significantly more on each dog than their adoption fee. Adoption fee for HW positive dog also covers heartworm treatment at our partner vets.
Foster Program: Foster homes provide for the temporary care of a rescue until the dog is placed into a loving, forever home. For more information on becoming a foster parent, and our Foster Program, visit http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/foster/ or email our Foster Coordinator at foster@k-9lifesavers.org
Sponsor Me! Make a tax-deductible donation today by visiting us at http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/donate/ . Donations help us offset boarding costs and additional medical treatment for those dogs who need it. K-9 Lifesavers receives NO federal funding and survive with your generous support!
For more information on K-9 Lifesavers, or to view a complete listing of all our Adoptable Dogs, visit our website at www.k-9lifesavers.org.
Please "like" our Facebook Page for the most current events and new dogs.
Thank you for considering a rescue dog!

animal.description:
IMPORTANT!!!   All adoptions are by appointment only going forward and are spaced 30 minutes apart. PLEASE call the shelter directly during business hours for more information (see number below).  You need to make sure that the animal in which you have an interest is still available and to set up an appointment to meet the specific animal.  Once you arrive at the shelter for your scheduled appointment, please follow the directions that you were given over the telephone. If you are running late for your appointment or will be unable to make your scheduled appointment time, notify staff immediately. This will enable them to schedule that time for another prospective adoptive family. If necessary, they will be able to reschedule your appointment to a more convenient time.  

ROCKY is such a sweetheart!  Look at that great smile in his happy face!  He is listed as an 18-month old Boxer/Jack Russell Terrier x dog.  His coloring is tan/white and he is short-haired which makes him easy to maintain.  He has not yet been neutered, so...that has to be done before you can take him home with you.  He is well worth the wait!  Call to schedule your adoption appointment and see for yourself.

Adoption fees are $80 for dogs.  Cat adoption fees are $50. Cash or check only. Please be sure to take the exact amount with you.

NOTE: All shelter fees are under review and may be changed or modified at any time without advance notice.

The shelter routinely vaccinates all healthy appearing animals upon their arrival at the shelter and deworms them.  Any animals not already spayed/neutered must have the procedure done through the veterinary clinic that contracts with the county before that animal can be released from the clinic to the new family. By state law, animals old enough to be given a rabies vaccine, must have that vaccine done, as well.  The vaccine is given by the veterinary clinic staff at a separate cost to the adoptive family. 

Hold periods for every incoming animal vary for several reasons including, but not limited to, whether the animal came in from the Cumberland County area, or from the City of Crossville, which contracts with the county for its animal shelter services.  Check with the staff to verify the availability date of every animal for which you have an interest.

For more information on this pet, call the shelter at (931)484-8525. The shelter is open Monday, Tuesday, Thursday, Friday, and Saturday from 10am to 2pm. Closed Wednesday and Sunday and county observed holidays.

animal.description:
Mama-zzzz!  This  girl  came  to us  as  a pregnant street  stray which no one  claimed  She  was  very  timid and  unsure. After raising her pups  and  being on her  own  again  she  started  building  friendships with other dogs.  Her favorite  is  Rocky James.  We  would like  nothing more  for them to tie the knot  and  stay together but we  know  the  chances  of that are slim.
We  know  nothing  of Mama-zzz  past  but  we  do  know  she  does  better in situations  and  surroundings  that  are familiar  to her. Loud  noises and  sudden  happenings  frighten.  She  shouldn't  be  forced  into situations  she  is  unsure  of..  time  and  coaxing  work  best She walks  well on a leash  but is  not adventuresome  and prefers  the same  familiar short walk. . Mama-zzz is more  comfortable  around woman than men. Her new  lifestyle  should  be one  that creates  a secure environment, structure  and routine.  She  is  very sweet  and  will  just  need  a patient and understanding owner  that  will build  her  confidence level.  Once  you know  her  she will win and melt your heart and  you will have  a gentle lifelong companion.  Please  inquire  at  haltrescue@gmail.com
Our adoption fee is $250  and  helps  us  save  other dogs  and  support  our  rescue  work!

Hint, hint!

I am spayed, up to date on vaccines, healthy and microchipped.

animal.description:
Bart / Male / 2 Years / 20 lbs / Street Mix / Mississauga

Meet Bart! Bart was rescued during a very bad storm, when he tried to take shelter in a gas station. He was malnourished at the time and in desperate need of care. Once in the loving hands of our partner shelter, Bart began to come out of his shell and thrive! Bart is a special guy and needs an equally special family to join him on his training journey. He has nothing but potential ahead of him and with the right support, will be an incredible companion.

Bart falls in love fast with anyone and everyone he meets. He is a social guy and loves to be around humans. Bart has never met a toy he doesn’t like, and will happily play by himself or with his humans. Bart is described as playful, friendly, cuddly, curious smart and trainable. He is a very active dude and would do best with a family who shares his love of adventure!

Bart is friendly with people and is always up for making a new friend. He gets acquainted quickly and will want to cuddle almost immediately. He has not been tested with children but would do well with dog savvy children that are 14+.

Bart is a major puller on leash, his leash manners and etiquette will need continued work. Although he is obedient and eager to please inside, he is very distracted and alert while he is outside. He is reactive (barking, lunging, growling) to dogs or squirrels. He can be dog selective and needs proper introductions. His fosters have done an incredible job setting him up for success so far, but it needs to be understood that this is an ongoing journey with Bart. He is powerful when he is focused on something and will need a strong handler (no kids) to walk him. Adopters will have the opportunity to speak with our behavioural support team to discuss his current training structure.

Inside the home Bart is always focused on his humans. He is very smart, food motivated and loves to learn. He has already mastered sit, down, focus, stay and paw. He has perfect recall when he is indoors. Given he receives adequate opportunities to use the washroom, he is full potty trained. However he will mark inside the home if left unsupervised, so he needs consistent interruption and redirection.

Bart’s ideal family would be home more often than not, or have a flexible schedule to suit his needs. He will need a family with dog experience and who will hire a personal trainer as needed. Bart will need a detached home, with a fully fenced backyard for him to have consistent potty breaks and a secured area to play. He is only looking for homes that are outside of the city.

While living as a stray, Bart suffered a pelvis fracture of unknown origin. Xrays reveal the injury has healed, but it does seem to cause some degree of discomfort. He does not like to be pet or touched in the area and has air snapped when someone forgets the rules. Bart is taking gabapentin for pain management and it is recommended his adopters continue in-home physio therapy to build muscle tone.

If you’re interested in adopting Bart please apply at https://www.fetchandreleash.ca/adoption-info#adoption-form

Bart’s adoption fee is $700. To learn more about our adoption fees and the adoption process, please visit our FAQs at https://www.fetchandreleash.ca/about-us#about-faqs.

animal.description:
BONES IS ON HOLD. 

Bones is a medium-haired, black and tan German Shepherd who was born in March 2020. He weighs a whopping SEVENTY-THREE POUNDS and still has more growing left! :O

Bones was brought to our shelter because he's a farm dog and he was having trouble staying on the farm. His previous owner said that they tried an electric fence and a shock collar, but Bones kept running off the property.

Bones is a quiet boy. The other two hounds bark their heads off, but not Bones!

Bones LOVES to play! He either hasn't gotten the hang of fetch, or he REALLY likes the game keep-away :P Being outside doesn't really bother him, so we know when he's pawing at the door that he's ready to come back inside.

We learned Bones' first day that he loves to shred soft dog toys, so he only gets those under supervision and with a garbage bag in hand :P Bones is true to his name and loves bones :D

He's scheduled to be neutered on 3-2-21. His adoption fee is $200, and we accept cash or check.

Bones is up-to-date on his vaccinations, will be neutered on 3-2-21, up-to-date on his flea and tick preventative, tested negative for heartworm, is up-to-date on his heartworm preventative, will be microchipped, and is potty trained.

animal.description:
NAME: Lily Owens

AGE/GENDER: 5 mos (estimate), Female

BREED: Unknown mix

ESTIMATED ADULT WEIGHT: 40ish lbs

ADOPTION DONATION: $525.00

HEALTH: Lily is spayed, microchipped, flea treated, dewormed, and is current on vaccines.

TEMPERAMENT: Playful and mischievous when comfortable. Shy in new environments.

HOUSE TRAINING: Not yet. She is a baby so she'll need a consistent schedule with multiple opportunities daily to go outside while she works on it. Puppies should not be considered reliable in regard to house training until 6-12 months of age. They're a lot like toddlers, who require diapers.

CRATE TRAINING: Good, she's young and trainable.

OTHER DOGS: Good! She will need continued socialization, like all puppies.

CATS: Unknown but she is a puppy and can be trained to co-exist.

CHILDREN: Dog-respectful children, 8 and older

HEALTH: Lily is healthy. She is altered, microchipped, flea treated, and dewormed. She has been given vaccination boosters in our care; however, adoptive families will be responsible for the remaining vaccinations that puppies need. Your adoption donation goes toward the cost of her vet care as well as transportation and general care costs.

HISTORY: Lily came to us from Mexico where she was found and saved. Motley Zoo Animal Rescue was asked to find them a great forever family and that is exactly what we plan to do.

NOTES FROM FOSTER HOME: Lily is getting more active and beginning to explore her foster's home.

NOTES FROM FOSTER HOME: Lily is a very shy gal who does not like being alone. She loves her people and will need training in order to stave off separation anxiety.
Lily is a puppy so she's playful and has a lot of puppy energy. She is super cute and fun, but a lot of work. Her forever family should be committed to lots of training - obedience, house training, and socialization. This will ensure that Lily grows into a confident, well behaved adult. Puppies' personalities are dependent on their environment, and the structure and training they are given, in addition to socialization. Their personalities continue to grow and be shaped by their new adoptive families. Puppy daycare and socialization classes or puppy kindergarten are highly recommended for their personal development. She will more than reward you for all your hard work with lots of love, loyalty, and laughs.

All dogs adopted from Motley Zoo come with a leash and either a Martingale collar or a harness, depending on each dog's particular needs.

ABOUT MOTLEY ZOO

Welcome to Motley Zoo Animal Rescue. We are a 501(c)(3) non-profit animal rescue organization that is run entirely by volunteers. Motley Zoo does not have a brick and mortar shelter location. Instead, all our rescue animals are cared for in private foster homes where the animals receive one-on-one care and attention in a home environment until permanent placement is found. Please email adopt@motleyzoo.org and request an adoption application and we will work toward approving you as an adopter with our rescue so that we can set a time for you to meet!

For more information, please visit www.motleyzoo.org.

Thank you for considering adopting a dog in need!

Woof,

The Motley Zoo Crew

Dog's Name: Matilda
Estimated Breed : Hound Mix
Approximate Age: 1 years
Approximate Weight: approx. 55 lbs
Currently Living at: Boarding
Adoption Fee: $300
DOG'S DESCRIPTION
Matilda is a gorgeous girl that loves people and other dogs. She gives great hugs and tries to keep her howling to a minimum. She would love to find a home with lots of space to run and play in addition to the ever so important loving family. She would do anything for a treat! Will you give this beauty a happy home?
Your new pet will require a refresher in house-training. K-9 Lifesavers strongly recommends all new adopters enroll their new pet into obedience training. This provides for an easier transition into a new home, ensures the dog remains well socialized, and helps form a bond between the dog and the new family.
Adoption fees cover basic vetting, spay/neuter surgery (for dogs over 6 months old), rabies, distemper/parvo vaccinations, treatment for worms, heartworm testing, monthly heartworm prevention and monthly flea/tick prevention (while the animal is in our care), and transport costs from high-kill shelter. Please note that on average, K-9 Lifesavers spend significantly more on each dog than their adoption fee. Adoption fee for HW positive dog also covers heartworm treatment at our partner vets.
Foster Program: Foster homes provide for the temporary care of a rescue until the dog is placed into a loving, forever home. For more information on becoming a foster parent, and our Foster Program, visit http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/foster/ or email our Foster Coordinator at foster@k-9lifesavers.org
Sponsor Me! Make a tax-deductible donation today by visiting us at http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/donate/ . Donations help us offset boarding costs and additional medical treatment for those dogs who need it. K-9 Lifesavers receives NO federal funding and survive with your generous support!
For more information on K-9 Lifesavers, or to view a complete listing of all our Adoptable Dogs, visit our website at www.k-9lifesavers.org.
Please "like" our Facebook Page for the most current events and new dogs.
Thank you for considering a rescue dog!

King is crate and house trained - and actually enjoys snoozing away in his crate for a few hours during the day. He walks relatively well on leash and mostly ignores other dogs. He is mild mannered with adults and children alike. He would do fine in a home with children - he isn't jumpy or mouthy - none of that silly puppy behavior! King would thrive in a home with humans who like routine and structure.

animal.description: Hi, my name is JACK FROST and I would love to meet you. I am a Neutered Male Labrador Retriever mix. The shelter staff think I am about 10 months old. I have been at the shelter since Jan 24, 2021. Meet Jack Frost! This sweet, sweet boy came to the shelter as a stray so shelter staff and volunteers are still getting to know him. Personality: Jack Frost is just the nicest pup you ever did meet! He loves his sweaters just as much as he loves his snuggles! History: His history with other dogs, cats, and small mammals is unknown. We always recommend SLOW and CAREFUL introductions over time to any resident pets. Energy levels: Jack Frost may look like Benjamin Button, but he is alllll puppy! He has energy to burn and will need a fairly active family to keep him out of trouble. Ideal home: He is looking for a home that is prepared to handle all things PUPPY. He would benefit from puppy classes with a qualified trainer. His family should be prepared for his ongoing medical (possible deafness, dermatitis and resolved entropion). Since he can`t hear the volume of his own voice, Jack Frost is not suited for apartment style living. Family: Jack Frost would do best in a home that has children that are old enough to handle his puppy behavior and jumpiness. All children under 12 years should be present to meet with him. Are you ready for some Frost in your life? Come down and meet him today!

animal.description:
Javert is a handsome male miniature poodle about 1 year old and 16 pounds. His owner couldn’t keep him and asked us to take him into our program. He’s shy at first with strangers but warms up quickly - a delightful poodle dog. 

IF YOU'RE INTERESTED IN ADOPTING THIS DOG:
Please go to our Website: Poodlerescueofhouston.org and see the section: "Steps 2 Adoption". There will be a drop down menu where you must read and meet all of the prerequisites. Next, read the "Steps To Adoption", fill out the "Interest Form" and submit it online. THIS IS THE ONLY WAY TO APPLY. Unfortunately, we are unable to respond to inquires made in any other way.

Poodle Rescue will contact you if we feel this dog, or a similar dog in our program, matches the specifications on your Questionnaire/Interest Form. Please keep in mind Poodles and Poodle Mixes are in high demand therefore the demand for them far outweigh the supply. If you do not hear from us please re-submit your Interest form quarterly as they are not recurring. Unfortunately, we cannot answer email or telephone inquiries about our available dogs.  Please be sure you have a current phone number listed on the questionnaire/Interest Form and the best time we can reach you. Adoption Fees vary.

All dogs are spayed/neutered, current on shots, parasite / heart worm disease tested (and treated if positive).  All dogs are microchipped, groomed and use a dog door at our facility.

We are presently not holding our regular Saturday adoption clinics due to the Covid-19 virus.  We are operating on a limited basis until further notice, but we are still adopting dogs out. We require an approved application before we consider anyone for an adoption - so filling out the application is your first step.   Different dogs and puppies go up for adoption EVERY WEEK so please feel free to visit the site and click on the Petfinder link for updates. Puppies and dogs up to 2 years old are $350. Dogs over 2 years old are $250. 100% of the adoption fees go to help us save more dogs.

animal.description:
COMING SOON. This dog is not ready for adoption yet but please follow us theREALbark on FaceBook and @therealbark on Instagram to see updates on his progress.

23 lb, 3 yr old Lusso was rescued from a canyon hillside where he had been living alone on a tattered mattress for 1 year, surviving by scavenging food. He has made a lot of progress since then but his road to emotional healing comes with a list “must haves”. Lusso must go to a calm, quiet home (no children) with at least one other well-tempered dog who can help him develop his confidence and feel safe. His adopter must be very dog saavy, experienced and patient with Lusso’s feral personality, providing him with structure and love. He must have a private, secure yard as he is still working on house training and can not be expected to use walks for his potty breaks for some time to come. Lusso is very scared of new people and gravitates to dogs, he has started walking on leash with another dog at his side, and is slowly working on car rides. This beautiful boy wants to be loved and wants very much to please but he needs to know he is safe at all times, and loved, in order to continue his journey to becoming a great companion. He is crate trained.

animal.description:
Ghost - Ready to be your new BOO 
    Awooo! Hello there, I’m Ghost. The hoomans say I am a 5 to 6 year old pitbull weighing a hefty 50lbs! Fully neutered and vaccinated, I am ready to go home today. I’m a very good boy on the leash, and am almost fully potty-trained… but sometimes I get so nervous I pee a little. Come on… who doesn’t do that? I love sleeping in my crate - it’s so much more comfy than the empty lot I called home before TCF rescued me. I was skin and bones when they found me, look at me now! 50lbs of soft belly just waiting for rubs. I don’t mind other doggos, as long as they stay away from my food bowl! That’s all me! I even warmed up to little hoomans… but I don’t have the whole cat thing figured out yet.
    I’m a happy, sleepy, and spunky boy. My favorite thing to do is sleep… bonus if it’s on the couch. Although I am very submissive, I can be a little overprotective… especially if you step up to my food bowl and you are a doggo! Other than that, I have a very mild temperament and show no signs of separation anxiety. I do like attention, and it would be ideal if you can give me lots of it!
    My paw-fect fur-ever home is wherever there is a big yard for me to sit around and sunbathe in. Work from home is not necessary but highly preferred - I want to be loved and pet all day long! Ideally, I would be the only doggo in a home, and if little hoomans must be involved, I prefer them to be 12 or older. It’s nothing personal, it’s just that I feel I deserve a little extra tender love and care!  My adoption fee is $300 and that includes vetting care. If you want get boo’d up, please fill out the form on the website here http://www.thecantufoundation.org/adopt.html.
