Our Adoption Form can be completed online at our website at https://savinggracenc.org/how-to-adopt/ .

An Adoption Form is required before setting up an appointment to meet with a potential adoptee or a foster home.

Sending an Adoption Form does not commit you to an adoption, it simply provides us with background information on potential homes.

If you'd like to donate to help cover the cost of care for these wonderful dogs awaiting new homes, please visit the donate page on our website at https://savinggracenc.org/donate-now/ .

Saving Grace is a small, non-profit 501-C3 organization operated by volunteers only. Most of our animals come from rural animal control shelters where lack of space and resources limit their time and adoption possibilities. Thank you for choosing Saving Grace! We look forward to helping you find your new companion and family member.

animal.description:
If you are hoping for a gentle boy to be your companion, Squeeky may just be the pyrfect boy for you. Don't be fooled by his name, as Squeeky is not squeaky at all! In fact, he is a mellow boy who settles easily and gets along well with everyone. Even though Squeeky was raised on a farm with no human interaction, he has excellent house manners and has adjusted exceptionally well since coming into rescue. He is dedicated to be part of the pack, and is quick to learn how to navigate life with his people and their habits. Squeeky has had hip surgery due to an accident, but he has since recovered well. Nonetheless, it would be in Squeeky's best interests for his furever family to continue to ensure he maintains good functioning of his joints so as to have the best quality of life as a family companion. This sweet boy is easy-going and content to hang out on a rug by your feet as you work or curl up with a good book. If you are up for it, he will be more than delighted to show you his fantastic leash manners. Will you give this boy a chance to bring you love and joy for years to come? We are pawsitive you will not be disappointed!

NYS Registered Rescue # RR102
View full listing, fee and online application at - www.nationalpyr.org/adoptable-dogs (sorry, no phone submissions, but if you would like more information you can email us at renpyrgroup@yahoo.com).

Secure VISIBLE fencing is required; invisible fencing WILL NOT contain this breed. 

Our goal is to assess every application on its own merits. Key considerations are: 1) the experience of the applicant with large breed dogs 2) children in the household or regularly visiting the household are ready for a large-breed dog who is a guardian by nature (www.nationalpyr.org/know-the-breed) and 3) the sex of other dogs currently residing in the household to avoid same-sex aggression issues. For puppies under six months old, the applicant’s ability to socialize the puppy with older dogs is a priority.
animal.name: Squeeky in NY - Sweet, Easy-Going Boy!

animal.description: Meet Coffee Bean! This sweet girl is around 2 years old and looks to be a Terrier mix likely with several other breeds. She came to Labs and More with her two puppies who are now around 2 months old. She has been a great mama but is ready to put parenthood behind her and find her forever home. Coffee Bean is sweet and cuddly. She loves to go for walks and play with her puppies. She is very affectionate with people and takes treats gently. Coffee Bean is good with the cats she is fostered with and gets along with other dogs. If you think you are ready to add to your family by adopting Coffee Bean, then fill out an adoption application on our website today! If you are already approved with a coach or have adopted from us before, please reach out to your coach for the next steps. Your interest in adopting a rescued dog or puppy from Labs and More Rescue is appreciated! Please find our adoption information at www.labsandmore.org. Your adoption donation provides funding for Labs and More, a nonprofit organization which is supported, solely by Volunteers and funded by donations. Good news is your adoption donation can be considered tax deductible. So much care is provided to your new dog prior to the adoption, including: spay and neuter, microchip, veterinarian visit(s), vaccinations, and other medical care as needed. Many of the dogs we rescue require extensive surgeries and care prior to adoption. Please understand we are unable to predict future behavior or medical needs of your adopted dog. We provide no guarantees regarding behavior, breed, or age of the dogs. Thank you for rescuing.Thank you for looking to Adopt a Labrador Retriever or other Mixed Breed Dog from California Labradors Retrievers and More Rescue. Please take a moment and go to www.labsandmore.org and click on Adopt to complete our online dog adoption application. If you have any questions email us at doginfo@labsandmore.org or call us at 858-273-5386. Thank you for looking to a rescue group to fulfill your dream of adding a new dog to your life! Dogs + Love = Family

animal.description:
Mia is a wonderful dog, ready for her forever home. She’s been very friendly with all the people and dogs she has met. She's about 9 months old and still has a lot of puppy behavior (like chewing on things!). But she's eager to learn and is starting to recognize things that aren't appropriate chew toys. Mia is very willing to listen and is learning new commands and skills and needs an adopter looking to continue training with her. She's walking well on leash and is good in her kennel. She is not reactive around goats or chickens.

Mia weighs about 35 lbs and has a long tail. She's spayed, vaccinated, and microchipped. She tested negative for heartworms and is taking heartworm prevention.

Thanks for considering a dog from Texas Cattle Dog Rescue! We place heelers all over the state of Texas.

If you're interested in one of our dogs, please first complete our adoption application. You can download it at www.texascattledogrescue.com/adopt.html. Our standard adoption fee is $250 +tax for adult dogs, $300 +tax for puppies. Our dogs will be spayed or neutered, vaccinated and heartworm tested before going to a new home. We conduct a home visit to help match up the right dog with the right owner. For more information, visit our website www.texascattledogrescue.com.  Email adopt@texascattledogrescue.com if you have questions.

animal.description: Hi! My name is Winston! I was rescued by an animal shelter in South Carolina before arriving at Big Dog Ranch Rescue. I play well in playgroup and love to interact with other dogs. The staff at the shelter say that I am an "awesome dog!." My absolute favorite thing in the entire world are tennis balls and if you're willing to sit and throw one, I will chase it forever! I am a very good boy and I love to play with all other dogs, regardless of size. I have an EXTREMELY HIGH PREY DRIVE and should not be placed in a home with cats or other small animals. I could be an excellent family dog and would be absolutely able to live happily with children of any age. I could be a good pick for any adopter and I think that I would be happiest living in an environment where I would have the ability to run around freely with my new family outdoors (but must have secure fencing because if I see something to chase, I will absolutely go for it!). Whether it is a busy household or a quiet one is not important to me, as long as there are lots of people for me to play with and give love to. I love to go for long leashed walks, cuddle up on the couch and take a nice nap, and am always ready to participate in anything active.

animal.description: Hi! My name is Angel! I was rescued in Puerto Rico before arriving at the Big Dog Ranch Rescue. I'm a young puppy with lots of energy and spunk! I love to run around and play! I'm friendly and happy and just want to get to know you. Aside from having tons of energy, sometimes I can be loud, as I don't know how to control my barking yet. You have to remember, I'm a lot like a baby and have not necessarily adapted to a schedule yet so you may find that I'm staying up in my crate at night, and sleeping during the day. I need lots of direction and training, and that doesn't just mean puppy pre-school classes. I need you to show me the right and wrong things to do. Please don't be mad if in the process I wind up chewing some of your belongings or if I have accidents in the house - I promise I will get the hang of things! I require LOTS of time, energy, and patience, but my sweet little face makes it all worth it! This is a learning curve for us both but I promise that if you put the time and energy into helping me grow big and strong, you'll wind up with a wonderful little best friend for life.

animal.description: Hi! My name is Danny! I was rescued in China before arriving at the Big Dog Ranch Rescue! I am a very good boy but I can sometimes be quite protective over my space and my people so I think I would benefit the most from an experienced dog owner who is going to be able to help me learn that I'm not at risk of losing anything. I would be happiest living in a home with a great big yard, or even a farm, for me to run around and play in. That being said, I would need a home with a very secure fence, because I have been known to be quite the escape artist. I am also not unfamiliar to some more negative behaviors like chewing and digging, but I think that with some help I can learn to stop doing that sort of thing. I think that I'd be happy in a busy home with lots of things going on and even though I can be protective, I am also a very friendly pup who likes to receive visitors. I may even be the type of pup that you bring out and about with you on your daily activities. I could certainly benefit from continued training, particularly as it relates to potty-training, but I have learned to love long-leashed walks during my time here at the ranch. My favorite activities include playing fetch, going for long walks or runs, swimming, playing with toys, and most definitely cuddling up on the couch with someone that loves me!

animal.description:
Hi my name is Cysialy but my foster family calls me Ladybug. I am a very smart confident girl  who is learning new things everyday. I am about 6 lbs and definitely a mix of breeds!  Because I came into the shelter at 6 weeks by myself my foster family is working very hard on teaching me to trust and the ways of living with a family. Since I did not spend enough time with my mom and siblings I do like to chew more than normal. But, every day my foster mama tells me I am doing such a good job and that I am a good girl! Because I am a beagle mix I would do best with a fenced in yard. Since I do like to chew and my puppy bites are a little bit harder than normal I would do best in a home without small kids. I would do best with someone who is experience with training dogs. Someone who will be patient with me and understand that I need extra TLC. In time I promise you I will be your best friend and love you unconditionally. My foster mom has been working with a trainer through a sound begging and I am learning so much! I am doing really well on my housebreaking as well - yay! 

Cysialy should be in a home with a fully fenced in yard and kids 10+. Experienced owners preferred and if there is a resident dog, a balanced, calm one would be best. 



The adoption fee of $500 will include spay/neuter, microchip, age appropriate/required vaccinations, treatment for heartworm and any other necessary medical treatment to assure a healthy new pup for your family.


IMPORTANT DISCLAIMER: Although we do our best to describe breed, since our pups all come from shelters we can not and will not make any guarantee on breed or size. We can tell you that they are 100% RESCUED! And that is the BEST breed!

If you are interested in adopting/meeting , please visit our website at www.starfishanimalrescue.com or you may complete the online adoption application on our Facebook Page https://www.facebook.com/starfishanimalrescue/app/134425496630143/?ref=page_internal Once you complete and submit your dog adoption application we will set up an appointment to meet this pup!  (the Facebook application will not load from a mobile phone, you must be on a desktop or laptop for this)

*please note that we are a foster home based rescue and we do home visits as part of the adoption process - we are unable to adopt to families who live outside of the Chicago and surrounding suburbs. Thank you for your understanding.

animal.description:
Apply to adopt at leadrescue.org. We do not adopt out of state and only adopt in Illinois within 50 miles of downtown Chicago.

The Landlord Grinch Who Stole the Christmas  Dog

Ok so there was no actual stealing of a dog. But there is a loss of holiday cheer and spirit now that another dog was evicted from the only home he knows. And yes, I wrote this story about a different dog that we eventually never got, but the story is an all to common one and didn’t want to delete it.

I was messaged about a dog who was a present. But I guess he wasn’t allowed to live where he did. Not sure if there was a size restriction or if it just was a no dog building. Although they had him for a year, all we ever hear is the landlord changed their mind. Ain’t there some type of protection against this? I didn’t get too far in the convo because I know having to give up a beloved family member is hard enough. Since he was available as soon as they signed him over, our foster opted to get him within the hour. He wouldn’t get sick, feel “completely” sad, and definitely has no idea what it’s like to feel alone.

Tugboat is a 3 year old, 40 lb Pug/Corgi/Bulldog mix and my golly Ms. Dolly, where can I get one for myself in 10 years? His first night he humped everything from the couch cushions to the poor two little boys. They got an advance education on the birds and the bees. What a way to make yourself at home with complete strangers.

Our impression of Tugboat is that he would do best in a quiet home with either one or a couple people, kids, and a co-existy type of dog or no dog. He was pretty barky when some plumbers came by but then he wanted to follow them throughout the house. He is still just trying to adjust, wondering where the people he loved for a year went. But even so, after only one day with his fosters, he seems to be pretty attached to the adults vs the kids. I mean the adult legs are probably more stable for the hump compared to a screaming child who is like what is going on?! He also really, really loves going for walks despite his marshmallow puffs for legs and when he does walk, he just glides alongside with you.

But yeah, you would think because the Grinch had his own dog, things could have been swept down the chimney and Tugboat could have stayed. But since this is real life, this nugget is actually available to find his new home away from Whoville. Apply to adopt Tugboat at leadrescue.org!

animal.description:
Nino ACCT-A-79871

Intake Reason: Owner Surrender (Bite Incident)
Sex: Male
Age: 4 years
Altered: No

Meet Nino! This timid boy is about 4 years old and is medium sized. Nino is very house-trained, and is working hard to stay that way during his time at the shelter. 
Nino is a very polite leash-walker, and he enjoys going for long, leisurely walks! He enjoys peanut butter, bones, good sniffs, and comfy blankets! 
Nino is as sweet as can be, but is very scared in his kennel. He is also easily startled by sudden and/or loud noises inside and outside. We are working with him on gaining confidence and he is already beginning to open up a little bit at a time.
Nino has likely never known what it feels like to be safe and loved, but we have promised him that his best days are still to come. Nino cannot wait for his foster or forever family to scoop him up and take him home - could you be the one to give this sweet boy his happily ever after? 
Please contact his penpal at costa.alexandrab@gmail.com for more information! 

***VIDEOS***
Nino getting some cuddles: https://youtu.be/LIrjfxgHH8Y
Nino enjoying his bone: https://youtu.be/Q9ZneDioaNY
Nino practicing skills: https://youtu.be/0WUDD-SwGrM
Nino takes treats (like the gentleman he is!): https://youtu.be/DOAFHWx9CXs
Nino walking: https://youtu.be/9HLVfsFXjjs
Nino tries out the water!: https://youtu.be/KokK_j1_5QU

Medical Observations: 
1/15 (Vet Check) -- Patient has been on Trazodone and appears to benefit from medication. May consider extension for duration of stay in shelter.
1/8 (Vet Check) -- (Visual exam only) Patient is currently on Trazodone and appears to benefit from medication. May consider extension for duration of stay in shelter.
12/18 (Vet Check) -- Generalized erythema observed may be secondary to allergies v. excited behavior. Previous pyoderma has resolved - patchy alopecia seen may continue to improve or remain permanent. 
12/11 (Vet Check) -- Patient appears calm and easily approachable - will likely benefit from Trazodone extension
12/3 (Vet Check) -- The patient's kennel presence has improved significantly in care. He may be benefitting from trazodone administration, or has adjusted to the shelter environment. Trazodone will be continued.
11/26 (Vet Check) -- Patient presents with mild pyoderma likely secondary to allergies. He appeared quite nervous in the kennel (shaking and lip licking) but eventually allowed to be taken out for examination. Will benefit from Trazodone for duration of stay in the shelter.
11/25 (Intake Exam) -- Skin irritation; yeast on belly. Tartar on teeth.

Behavior Observations: 
1/14 (Per Volunteer) -- Nino and I spent the afternoon together, traveling from the shelter to Neshaminy Park (about 30 minutes), walking in the park for about 2 hours, and then traveling back to the shelter. In the car on the way to the park, Nino never barked or scratched to get out of the car, despite being unsettled in a new environment. He just paced a bit in the backseat and seemed to have trouble sitting still with so much stimulation outside. He had also just come out of his kennel, so his stress and energy levels were both high.
Once we arrived at the park, Nino was happy to be outside and took in ALL the sniffs! His nose was almost always down on the ground enjoying the new smells for the first 30 minutes of our walk. We walked the trails for about an hour, and Nino was on high alert for this time, noticing each stranger who passed by. I attempted to give treats and get his attention, but he was too interested in our surroundings to be able to focus or take any treats. He was still very much enjoying the walk, though, and even dipped his feet into the water when we walked to the coast! 
After about an hour of walking, Nino's overall demeanor noticeably shifted. He began responding to my calls for attention and began taking treats! Once I saw that he had become more relaxed, we practiced some training and played some attention games - and he showed me what a smarty pants he is! We practiced "sit" with the clicker, and we also worked on name recall, and he did incredibly well with both. 
Up until the last 45 minutes or so, we had not come across any other dogs. Once we were set up at a picnic table (in a grassy area removed from the paths) practicing these skills, we began seeing dogs go by, but they were far enough away that I was able to recall Nino's attention when he was becoming fixated. It was amazing to see him begin turning toward me (away from the trigger) after the first few times we tried it! We were far enough away from the triggers that once he understood that turning to me meant treats & rewards, he could take his attention off of the dog - it was amazing to watch! 
After we practiced for awhile, Nino enjoyed a yummy bone and some time just relaxing and getting pets - this was also a HUGE step. When I first met Nino about 2 weeks ago, he wouldn't really come near me and was extremely hand shy. To see him open up like this is such a privilege - I'm tearing up just thinking about him! 
Then we made our way back to the car for the trip back to the shelter. Once we arrived, we met Rob in the parking lot, and Nino ran right up to him for pets! It was amazing! He wasn't shy and eagerly wanted to greet him. While it always breaks my heart to bring him back, this was really a wonderful day and I can't wait for our next time together. 
1/12 (Per Foster Staff) -- Kennel Presentation: Easy to leash/social - Standing at kennel door with tail wagging. Attempted to push out several times but was easily leashed. On return to kennel, Nino jumped up on the neighboring dog's kennel and sniffed her through the door with his tail wagging. He was interested in her but handler was able to redirect him by calling him and tugging the leash gently. Entered kennel without issue. Walks well on the leash with minimal pulling, but occasionally pulls towards interesting smells or other animals (passed a cat in the parking lot and he pulled hard towards it). Loose/Allows all handling - Allowed allover handling, loves butt scratches! Solicits some attention and pets by approaching handler with tail wagging, but is timid. Engages in tag. Chased a few toys when tossed, but minimal interest. Likes busy bones and chicken jerky treats -- will sit for tasty treats. Evaluated gold. Recommend Playgroup - Had a positive interaction with his neighboring dog in the kennel.
12/22 (Per Staff) -- At front of kennel on approach with tail wagging. Easily leashed and removed from kennel. Walks nicely on leash. In yard, takes a minute of coaxing before he will approach handler but then accepts slow pets with slightly stiff body. No issues returning to kennel. In kennel, loosens up and allows pets again with loose body. Making Available.
12/18 (Per Vet) -- very excited, able to take out of kennel without issue
12/13 (Per Staff)-- He was timid coming out the kennel but allowed himself to be leashed easily. He walked outside and did not pull on the leash, he did not solicit pets and when a volunteer handler first reached out to have him sniff him, he slinked back a little but then sniffed. With some time he warmed up and walked well on the leash and participated in the photoshoot. He was returned easily to the kennel, allowing for pets and for the leash to be easily removed. 
12/11 (Per vet) -- calm, tail wagging; no barking and panting
12/6 (Per Staff) -- On walk, encountered dog and was reactive, lunging and hard barking.
12/6 (Per Staff) -- Kennel Presentation: Easy to leash/social. Loose and wiggly at front of kennel. Easy to leash and remove from kennel. Easy to return and unleash.
Leash Skills: Pulls Moderately On Leash
Handleability: Tense/Allows all handling. Allows handling all over but tense throughout interaction. Does lean into handler when getting his rear scratched.
Tag: Engages in play
Toys: No interest
Color Level: Blue
12/3 (Per Vet) -- Calm at kennel front, wagging tail. No barking or growling
12/1 (Per Staff) -- Nervous. Shaking when handler approaches but does approach kennel front. No interest in treats. Does not retreat when handler opens kennel door and presents leash. Easily leashed but does not move forward to exit kennel immediately. Allows handler to sit in kennel opening with him and then approaches to sniff handler. Handler moves to floor and, after initial hesitation, Nino follows handler out of kennel. Returning to kennel, Nino follows handler in and is easily unleashed. Leash Skills: Pulls Minimally On Leash
Handleability: Tense/Allows all handling. After urinating and defecating in yard, explores yard and then returns to handler. Is still shaking and tense but allows pets all over starting slowly from rear and then up to front of body. After two to three minutes of handling, starts to lean into pets and loosens up a bit. Tenses at loud noises from the street.
11/29 (Per Staff) -- Shaking and whale eyed in kennel when approached. No interest in treats either from hand or dropped on kennel floor. Refused to approach when leash was presented and kennel door was opened. Remained tense, shaking, whale eyed and growling but did not move towards or away from handler. Ended interaction.
11/26 (Per Vet) -- nervous, shaking and lip licking in corner of kennel but allowed to be taken out of kennel for examination; tolerated examination but remained cautious
11/25 (Per Vet) -- Friendly; fearful; BAR.
11/24 (Per Owners) -- Bite case, protective of toys, aggressive.

**BITE DETAILS** 
11/24 -- The victim took mail from the dog when she attempted to give the mail back to the dog he bit her right hand.

animal.description:
Hiiii, friends!! I'm Lasagna. TLP rescued me with just minutes to spare -- literally!! I was scheduled to be EU'd for space that afternoon when TLP magically found a way to save me. I am so glad they did, because I am truly the world's happiest girl and I have so much love to give.

I adore everyone I meet. I might be a little shy at first, but I'll still come up and ask for love. I especially like to have my belly rubbed! I'm extra extra playful, so I would do best with bigger kiddos who can handle my size.

I'm a real dog's dog! I looooove my dog pals -- big, small, male, female -- they're all my best friends, as far as I'm concerned. My favorite thing is to spend the morning romping around with other dogs, then curling up with (OK, on top of) them for a nap. I'm currently being treated for heartworms, so it's super important that I don't play too hard right now. I'm especially curious about chasing kitties ... I probably shouldn't go to a home with cats.

I love to go on adventures, as long as you promise to let me ride shotgun. There's nothing better than getting to look out the window as the world rolls by. I'm awesome on the leash (I might pull if I see a squirrel, but it's easy to get my attention) and I'm an angel in my crate. I don't mind snoozing in there for hours while you're away! I'm a smart lady and I know all my basic commands -- and then some! I even know roll over (I figured out fast that "roll over" is an excellent way to get more belly rubs). 

I have the goofiest ears, but I'm sooper srs about cuddling. In the evenings, I'm all about getting those couch cuddles!! I love to get up on the couch with my foster family and snuggle for hours. 

Dog-friendly, playful, adventurous and super affectionate? I'm pretty much the ultimate good girl. Apply to meet me!!

animal.description:
Delilah is a 9-week-old mixed breed rescued from a high-kill shelter. This dog is current on vaccinations, microchipped, and spayed/neutered. This puppy is currently in foster care learning home etiquette, kennel training, and housebreaking. We would love for you to meet this puppy and see if it might be a good fit for your home. 

The first step to adoption is completing an adoption application on our website at www.bounceanimalrescue.org. Pending approval, your application is valid for 1 year, and you will be eligible to request a hold on an individual animal. The hold does not require that you adopt the animal, but ensures you get to meet and make an adoption decision prior to other applicants. Hold times cannot exceed 5 days. Also pending approval, you will be able to acquire foster home contact information, so you inquire on personalities of specific animals.

***COVID-19 Update: While we typically host weekly Saturday adoption events, in order to follow the CDC's recommendation for COVID-19 protocols, we will be suspending our weekly Saturday adoption events until given the clear. Adoptions for individual animals will occur by private adoption appointment and/or adoption handoff. Appointments and handoffs are scheduled pending staff, foster home, and vetting schedules. Because we are 100% foster-based, adoption appointments and handoffs are only offered for individual animals. When adopting at an appointment, please be aware that you will be taking the animal home that day. We can not hold animals to be picked up at a later date.

Due to CDC's recommended COVID-19 protocols, we are highly encouraging foster homes and adopters to speak with one another via phone or video chat to ensure compatible matches and limit in-person contact. If meeting in person, our foster homes are encouraged to wear masks, socially distance, and choose an outdoor meeting spot. Should you want to proceed forward with the adoption, all adoption paperwork, medical records, and adoption fees are to be completed electronically. Quick and low-contact animal handoff is also being encouraged amongst foster homes and adopters. As always, we include a one-week trial period with all our adoptions. ***

Please note, we do not have the ability to process adoption applications at our adoption events, so please plan accordingly. If an application is submitted past 5pm on Monday-Thursday, it will begin review the following day. If submitted on Friday-Sunday, it will begin review on Monday. It takes approximately 48-72 hours for an application to be processed.

For additional questions regarding meeting this dog please contact us via text/email at 970.699.6772, or contact@bounceanimalrescue.org. We apologize for any inconvenience, but due to a high volume of inquiries, calls and voicemails regarding adoption will not be returned.

Thank you for choosing adoption! If you would like more information on our organization please visit our website at www.bounceanimalrescue.org.

animal.description:
Sweet Pea is a 1 year old female Boxer/Shepherd mix. She weighs 47 pounds. Back in July 2019, Sweet Pea was adopted from the Collierville Animal Shelter when she was a 9 week old puppy. Her former owners recently surrendered her because they couldn't care for her any longer. This wonderful girl is a little heartbroken and is learning to trust people again after being back in the shelter. For this reason, she can be shy when meeting new people. She is very gentle and if you sit beside her, she will lay her head in your lap and lick your hands. Everyone in the shelter is in love with her.  Although she is dog friendly, she does not like sharing a home with another dog. For that reason, she will need to be the only pet in the home. 

Update: since being at the shelter for a few weeks now, she has really opened up and has become super outgoing and playful! She seems to be housebroken and walks well on a leash.

ADOPTION HOURS:

animal.description:
Posted 1/25/2021. Hugh came to Furry Friends Network from a shelter after he was found as a stray.  He is thought to be 4-5 years old and is neutered and up to date with his vaccinations.  He is crate trained and housebroken.  He enjoys playing tug , chewing on bones and going for hikes. He lives with two adults, one cat and two 10 year old dogs.  Hugh would love for the resident dogs to play with him and is respectful, but the dogs have no interest.  He is learning basic commands and walks generally well on a leash.  He does get excited when he sees another dog but can be re-directed with treats.  Hugh has skin allergies that require bathing 1-2 times a week using a medicated soap and using an ear rinse 1-2 times a week.  He has been very well behaved in his foster home and is allowed total freedom.  He would love a yard and another dog to play with since he still has some young dog energy.  Give this guy a chance at finding a forever home!

Adoption application, home visit and adoption fee required. If you would like to apply for adoption, please complete the online application at www.furryfriendsnetwork.com. Look under ADOPT tab. Please also read our Core Values prior to applying, www.furryfriendsnetwork.com/adopt/our-expectations. Contact generalinfo@furryfriendsnetwork.com for questions or if issues are encountered with the adoption application or general adoption process.

Foster Homes are desperately needed in order to help more animals like this one. Please consider opening your heart and home to a homeless animal. To find out more about becoming a Foster Parent, see our website at www.furryfriendsnetwork.com. Look under VOLUNTEER tab.

animal.description:
Well hey there guys! 
My name’s Peanut ? and I am a 8 year old chihuahua mix. 

Now let me just tell you I am an absolute toot and just the most loving dog you will ever meet. Now don’t let my age scare you I have plenty of energy for some walkies which I definitely need so that I can lose some weight but I also love a good cuddle on the couch ? I am just a ball of happiness just waiting for my forever family! I am good with both large dogs and small dogs or id be perfectly okay as an only dog because well that just means more attention for me ? I am house trained and need to be let out a few times a day just like any normal dog. The crate is not my favorite place to be and I will cry a little but eventually I learn to settle. 

Since I am older in age I only eat soft food as I had to have a dental and lost a few teeth so it’s just easier for me. 

I am up to date on my shots, microchip and fixed for the adoption fee of $150. If interested in adopting me please email adoptions.spspca@gmail.com
